tandards, which can be found here:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/inxoah3ymmliqeg/Technical%20Standards%20Manual.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Technical Standards Manual[/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\nAs part of this technical analysis, you will have to:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Establish a Baseline of your energy/water use</li>\r\n	<li>Calculate savings from the installation of your project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe key metric in a PACE application is the Savings to Investment Ratio (SIR). In most cases, you must demonstrate an SIR &gt; 1, meaning that your project will pay for itself when taken over the life of the assessment. See the Technical Standards Manual for more information.\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li>Find an ITPR</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe energy/water savings analysis for your project will have to be confirmed by an Independent Third Party Engineer (ITPR). The ITPR must be a licensed PE in Texas and sign a statement confirming that he or she has no financial interest in your project. In addition, the ITPR must have one of the following certifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Assessment Professional (BEAP)</li>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Modeling Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Association of Energy Engineers (AEE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Manager (CEM)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Measurement and Verification Professional (CMVP)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Auditor (CEA)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Building Commissioning Association\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Commissioning Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n	<li>Closing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClosing on a PACE project will require several legal contracts. There will be required a legal contract between the property owner and the county, between the lender and the county. These contracts were developed through the PACE in a Box model which incorporated input from all parties including county staff, lenders, property owners, and contractors.\r\n\r\nThese contracts can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Lender Contract With County</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Owner Contract With County</a>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n	<li>File Assessment Lien</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe end result of a PACE project is a senior lien that will be filed with the local tax assessor/collector.\r\n\r\nThe form for this lien can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5yv0b22m48whn1/Notice%20of%20Assessment%20Lien.pdf?dl=0\">Tax Assessor/Collector Lien</a>', 'Preparing A PACE Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:35:43', '2015-04-06 21:35:43', '', '160', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=232', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('233', '2', '2015-04-06 21:36:47', '2015-04-06 21:36:47', '<ol>\r\n	<li>Decide on a project</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nFirst, you need to decide what energy/water efficiency measures you want to install. Generally, a PACE project must demonstrably reduce your energy/water consumption or generate distributed energy. This includes things such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Insulation</li>\r\n	<li>High-efficiency windows or doors</li>\r\n	<li>Automated energy control systems</li>\r\n	<li>HVAC modification or replacement</li>\r\n	<li>Caulking, weather-stripping or air sealing</li>\r\n	<li>Light fixture modifications</li>\r\n	<li>Water use efficiency improvements</li>\r\n	<li>Energy- or water-efficient manufacturing processes and/or equipment</li>\r\n	<li>Solar panels</li>\r\n	<li>Solar hot water</li>\r\n	<li>Gray water reuse</li>\r\n	<li>Rainwater collection system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe encourage you to explore multiple systems and put together a package of improvements for PACE.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a project in mind, take our Eligibility Assessment to see if your project might qualify.\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=17\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: check\"]Eligibility Screening Tool[/su_button]\r\n<br>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li>Find a contractor</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a contractor to help you with the design and installation of the project.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440.png\"><img class=\" wp-image-171  aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440-300x169.png\" alt=\"Texas Green Building Marketplace Logo\" width=\"239\" height=\"135\" /></a>[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=103\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: search\"]Find a Service Provider[/su_button]<br><br>\r\n\r\n<br><ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li>Find a lender</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a lender or capital provider to finance your PACE loan. A lender must meet the following qualifications:\r\n\r\nEligible third-party lenders may include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any federally insured depository institution such as a bank, savings bank, savings and loan association and federal or state credit union;</li>\r\n	<li>Any insurance company authorized to conduct business in one or more states;</li>\r\n	<li>Any registered investment company, registered business development company, or a Small Business Administration small business investment company;</li>\r\n	<li>Any publicly traded entity; or</li>\r\n	<li>Any private entity that:</li>\r\n	<li>Has a minimum net worth of $5 million;</li>\r\n	<li>Has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending (including multifamily lending), or has a lending officer that has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending; and</li>\r\n	<li>Can provide independent certification as to availability of funds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li>Obtain existing mortgagee consent</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf your property has a mortgage, you will need to get existing mortgagee consent before a PACE assessment can be applied. For help with obtaining mortgagee consent, see the following guide:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/r04u902y8605ye9/Mortgagee%20Support%20Handbook.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Mortgagee Support Handbook [/su_button]<br>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li>Technical analysis</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYour project will have to undergo an energy assessment as part of a PACE application. We follow the PACE in a Box Technical standards manual standards, which can be found here:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/inxoah3ymmliqeg/Technical%20Standards%20Manual.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Technical Standards Manual[/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\nAs part of this technical analysis, you will have to:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Establish a Baseline of your energy/water use</li>\r\n	<li>Calculate savings from the installation of your project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe key metric in a PACE application is the Savings to Investment Ratio (SIR). In most cases, you must demonstrate an SIR &gt; 1, meaning that your project will pay for itself when taken over the life of the assessment. See the Technical Standards Manual for more information.\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li>Find an ITPR</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe energy/water savings analysis for your project will have to be confirmed by an Independent Third Party Engineer (ITPR). The ITPR must be a licensed PE in Texas and sign a statement confirming that he or she has no financial interest in your project. In addition, the ITPR must have one of the following certifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Assessment Professional (BEAP)</li>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Modeling Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Association of Energy Engineers (AEE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Manager (CEM)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Measurement and Verification Professional (CMVP)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Auditor (CEA)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Building Commissioning Association\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Commissioning Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n	<li>Closing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClosing on a PACE project will require several legal contracts. There will be required a legal contract between the property owner and the county, between the lender and the county. These contracts were developed through the PACE in a Box model which incorporated input from all parties including county staff, lenders, property owners, and contractors.\r\n\r\nThese contracts can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Lender Contract With County</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Owner Contract With County</a>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n	<li>File Assessment Lien</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe end result of a PACE project is a senior lien that will be filed with the local tax assessor/collector.\r\n\r\nThe form for this lien can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5yv0b22m48whn1/Notice%20of%20Assessment%20Lien.pdf?dl=0\">Tax Assessor/Collector Lien</a>', 'Preparing A PACE Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:36:47', '2015-04-06 21:36:47', '', '160', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=233', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('234', '2', '2015-04-06 21:37:23', '2015-04-06 21:37:23', '<ol>\r\n	<li>Decide on a project</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nFirst, you need to decide what energy/water efficiency measures you want to install. Generally, a PACE project must demonstrably reduce your energy/water consumption or generate distributed energy. This includes things such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Insulation</li>\r\n	<li>High-efficiency windows or doors</li>\r\n	<li>Automated energy control systems</li>\r\n	<li>HVAC modification or replacement</li>\r\n	<li>Caulking, weather-stripping or air sealing</li>\r\n	<li>Light fixture modifications</li>\r\n	<li>Water use efficiency improvements</li>\r\n	<li>Energy- or water-efficient manufacturing processes and/or equipment</li>\r\n	<li>Solar panels</li>\r\n	<li>Solar hot water</li>\r\n	<li>Gray water reuse</li>\r\n	<li>Rainwater collection system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe encourage you to explore multiple systems and put together a package of improvements for PACE.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a project in mind, take our Eligibility Assessment to see if your project might qualify.\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=17\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: check\"]Eligibility Screening Tool[/su_button]\r\n<br>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li>Find a contractor</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a contractor to help you with the design and installation of the project.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440.png\"><img class=\" wp-image-171  aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440-300x169.png\" alt=\"Texas Green Building Marketplace Logo\" width=\"239\" height=\"135\" /></a>[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=103\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: search\"]Find a Service Provider[/su_button]<br><br>\r\n\r\n<br><ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li>Find a lender</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a lender or capital provider to finance your PACE loan. A lender must meet the following qualifications:\r\n\r\nEligible third-party lenders may include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any federally insured depository institution such as a bank, savings bank, savings and loan association and federal or state credit union;</li>\r\n	<li>Any insurance company authorized to conduct business in one or more states;</li>\r\n	<li>Any registered investment company, registered business development company, or a Small Business Administration small business investment company;</li>\r\n	<li>Any publicly traded entity; or</li>\r\n	<li>Any private entity that:</li>\r\n	<li>Has a minimum net worth of $5 million;</li>\r\n	<li>Has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending (including multifamily lending), or has a lending officer that has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending; and</li>\r\n	<li>Can provide independent certification as to availability of funds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br><ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li>Obtain existing mortgagee consent</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf your property has a mortgage, you will need to get existing mortgagee consent before a PACE assessment can be applied. For help with obtaining mortgagee consent, see the following guide:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/r04u902y8605ye9/Mortgagee%20Support%20Handbook.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Mortgagee Support Handbook [/su_button]<br>\r\n<br><ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<li>Technical analysis</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYour project will have to undergo an energy assessment as part of a PACE application. We follow the PACE in a Box Technical standards manual standards, which can be found here:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/inxoah3ymmliqeg/Technical%20Standards%20Manual.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Technical Standards Manual[/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\nAs part of this technical analysis, you will have to:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Establish a Baseline of your energy/water use</li>\r\n	<li>Calculate savings from the installation of your project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe key metric in a PACE application is the Savings to Investment Ratio (SIR). In most cases, you must demonstrate an SIR &gt; 1, meaning that your project will pay for itself when taken over the life of the assessment. See the Technical Standards Manual for more information.\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li>Find an ITPR</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe energy/water savings analysis for your project will have to be confirmed by an Independent Third Party Engineer (ITPR). The ITPR must be a licensed PE in Texas and sign a statement confirming that he or she has no financial interest in your project. In addition, the ITPR must have one of the following certifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Assessment Professional (BEAP)</li>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Modeling Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Association of Energy Engineers (AEE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Manager (CEM)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Measurement and Verification Professional (CMVP)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Auditor (CEA)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Building Commissioning Association\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Commissioning Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n	<li>Closing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClosing on a PACE project will require several legal contracts. There will be required a legal contract between the property owner and the county, between the lender and the county. These contracts were developed through the PACE in a Box model which incorporated input from all parties including county staff, lenders, property owners, and contractors.\r\n\r\nThese contracts can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Lender Contract With County</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Owner Contract With County</a>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n	<li>File Assessment Lien</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe end result of a PACE project is a senior lien that will be filed with the local tax assessor/collector.\r\n\r\nThe form for this lien can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5yv0b22m48whn1/Notice%20of%20Assessment%20Lien.pdf?dl=0\">Tax Assessor/Collector Lien</a>', 'Preparing A PACE Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:37:23', '2015-04-06 21:37:23', '', '160', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=234', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('235', '2', '2015-04-06 21:37:50', '2015-04-06 21:37:50', '<ol>\r\n	<li>Decide on a project</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nFirst, you need to decide what energy/water efficiency measures you want to install. Generally, a PACE project must demonstrably reduce your energy/water consumption or generate distributed energy. This includes things such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Insulation</li>\r\n	<li>High-efficiency windows or doors</li>\r\n	<li>Automated energy control systems</li>\r\n	<li>HVAC modification or replacement</li>\r\n	<li>Caulking, weather-stripping or air sealing</li>\r\n	<li>Light fixture modifications</li>\r\n	<li>Water use efficiency improvements</li>\r\n	<li>Energy- or water-efficient manufacturing processes and/or equipment</li>\r\n	<li>Solar panels</li>\r\n	<li>Solar hot water</li>\r\n	<li>Gray water reuse</li>\r\n	<li>Rainwater collection system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe encourage you to explore multiple systems and put together a package of improvements for PACE.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a project in mind, take our Eligibility Assessment to see if your project might qualify.\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=17\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: check\"]Eligibility Screening Tool[/su_button]\r\n<br>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li>Find a contractor</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a contractor to help you with the design and installation of the project.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440.png\"><img class=\" wp-image-171  aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440-300x169.png\" alt=\"Texas Green Building Marketplace Logo\" width=\"239\" height=\"135\" /></a>[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=103\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: search\"]Find a Service Provider[/su_button]<br><br>\r\n\r\n<br><ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li>Find a lender</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a lender or capital provider to finance your PACE loan. A lender must meet the following qualifications:\r\n\r\nEligible third-party lenders may include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any federally insured depository institution such as a bank, savings bank, savings and loan association and federal or state credit union;</li>\r\n	<li>Any insurance company authorized to conduct business in one or more states;</li>\r\n	<li>Any registered investment company, registered business development company, or a Small Business Administration small business investment company;</li>\r\n	<li>Any publicly traded entity; or</li>\r\n	<li>Any private entity that:</li>\r\n	<li>Has a minimum net worth of $5 million;</li>\r\n	<li>Has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending (including multifamily lending), or has a lending officer that has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending; and</li>\r\n	<li>Can provide independent certification as to availability of funds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br><ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li>Obtain existing mortgagee consent</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf your property has a mortgage, you will need to get existing mortgagee consent before a PACE assessment can be applied. For help with obtaining mortgagee consent, see the following guide:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/r04u902y8605ye9/Mortgagee%20Support%20Handbook.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Mortgagee Support Handbook [/su_button]<br>\r\n<br><ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<br><li>Technical analysis</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYour project will have to undergo an energy assessment as part of a PACE application. We follow the PACE in a Box Technical standards manual standards, which can be found here:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/inxoah3ymmliqeg/Technical%20Standards%20Manual.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Technical Standards Manual[/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\nAs part of this technical analysis, you will have to:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Establish a Baseline of your energy/water use</li>\r\n	<li>Calculate savings from the installation of your project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe key metric in a PACE application is the Savings to Investment Ratio (SIR). In most cases, you must demonstrate an SIR &gt; 1, meaning that your project will pay for itself when taken over the life of the assessment. See the Technical Standards Manual for more information.\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li>Find an ITPR</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe energy/water savings analysis for your project will have to be confirmed by an Independent Third Party Engineer (ITPR). The ITPR must be a licensed PE in Texas and sign a statement confirming that he or she has no financial interest in your project. In addition, the ITPR must have one of the following certifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Assessment Professional (BEAP)</li>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Modeling Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Association of Energy Engineers (AEE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Manager (CEM)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Measurement and Verification Professional (CMVP)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Auditor (CEA)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Building Commissioning Association\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Commissioning Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n	<li>Closing</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClosing on a PACE project will require several legal contracts. There will be required a legal contract between the property owner and the county, between the lender and the county. These contracts were developed through the PACE in a Box model which incorporated input from all parties including county staff, lenders, property owners, and contractors.\r\n\r\nThese contracts can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Lender Contract With County</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Owner Contract With County</a>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n	<li>File Assessment Lien</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe end result of a PACE project is a senior lien that will be filed with the local tax assessor/collector.\r\n\r\nThe form for this lien can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5yv0b22m48whn1/Notice%20of%20Assessment%20Lien.pdf?dl=0\">Tax Assessor/Collector Lien</a>', 'Preparing A PACE Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:37:50', '2015-04-06 21:37:50', '', '160', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=235', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('236', '2', '2015-04-06 21:40:11', '2015-04-06 21:40:11', '<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Decide on a project</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nFirst, you need to decide what energy/water efficiency measures you want to install. Generally, a PACE project must demonstrably reduce your energy/water consumption or generate distributed energy. This includes things such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Insulation</li>\r\n	<li>High-efficiency windows or doors</li>\r\n	<li>Automated energy control systems</li>\r\n	<li>HVAC modification or replacement</li>\r\n	<li>Caulking, weather-stripping or air sealing</li>\r\n	<li>Light fixture modifications</li>\r\n	<li>Water use efficiency improvements</li>\r\n	<li>Energy- or water-efficient manufacturing processes and/or equipment</li>\r\n	<li>Solar panels</li>\r\n	<li>Solar hot water</li>\r\n	<li>Gray water reuse</li>\r\n	<li>Rainwater collection system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe encourage you to explore multiple systems and put together a package of improvements for PACE.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a project in mind, take our Eligibility Assessment to see if your project might qualify.\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=17\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: check\"]Eligibility Screening Tool[/su_button]\r\n<br>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n	<li><strong>Find a contractor</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a contractor to help you with the design and installation of the project.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440.png\"><img class=\" wp-image-171  aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Texas_GreenBuilding_Marketplace_440-300x169.png\" alt=\"Texas Green Building Marketplace Logo\" width=\"239\" height=\"135\" /></a>[su_button url=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?page_id=103\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: search\"]Find a Service Provider[/su_button]<br><br>\r\n\r\n<br><ol start=\"3\">\r\n	<li><strong>Find a lender</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou will next need to find a lender or capital provider to finance your PACE loan. A lender must meet the following qualifications:\r\n\r\nEligible third-party lenders may include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Any federally insured depository institution such as a bank, savings bank, savings and loan association and federal or state credit union;</li>\r\n	<li>Any insurance company authorized to conduct business in one or more states;</li>\r\n	<li>Any registered investment company, registered business development company, or a Small Business Administration small business investment company;</li>\r\n	<li>Any publicly traded entity; or</li>\r\n	<li>Any private entity that:</li>\r\n	<li>Has a minimum net worth of $5 million;</li>\r\n	<li>Has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending (including multifamily lending), or has a lending officer that has at least three years’ experience in business or industrial lending or commercial real estate lending; and</li>\r\n	<li>Can provide independent certification as to availability of funds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<br><ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li><strong>Obtain existing mortgagee consent</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf your property has a mortgage, you will need to get existing mortgagee consent before a PACE assessment can be applied. For help with obtaining mortgagee consent, see the following guide:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/r04u902y8605ye9/Mortgagee%20Support%20Handbook.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Mortgagee Support Handbook [/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\n<br><ol start=\"5\">\r\n	<br><li><strong>Technical analysis</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYour project will have to undergo an energy assessment as part of a PACE application. We follow the PACE in a Box Technical standards manual standards, which can be found here:\r\n\r\n[su_button url=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/inxoah3ymmliqeg/Technical%20Standards%20Manual.pdf?dl=0\" target=\"blank\" style=\"flat\" background=\"#29789A\" size=\"7\" center=\"yes\" radius=\"0\" icon=\"icon: file\"]Technical Standards Manual[/su_button]<br>\r\n\r\nAs part of this technical analysis, you will have to:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Establish a Baseline of your energy/water use</li>\r\n	<li>Calculate savings from the installation of your project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe key metric in a PACE application is the Savings to Investment Ratio (SIR). In most cases, you must demonstrate an SIR &gt; 1, meaning that your project will pay for itself when taken over the life of the assessment. See the Technical Standards Manual for more information.\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li><strong>Find an ITPR</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe energy/water savings analysis for your project will have to be confirmed by an Independent Third Party Engineer (ITPR). The ITPR must be a licensed PE in Texas and sign a statement confirming that he or she has no financial interest in your project. In addition, the ITPR must have one of the following certifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>American Society of Heating, Refrigeration, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Assessment Professional (BEAP)</li>\r\n	<li>Building Energy Modeling Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Association of Energy Engineers (AEE)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Manager (CEM)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Measurement and Verification Professional (CMVP)</li>\r\n	<li>Certified Energy Auditor (CEA)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Building Commissioning Association\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified Commissioning Professional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n	<li><strong>Closing</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nClosing on a PACE project will require several legal contracts. There will be required a legal contract between the property owner and the county, between the lender and the county. These contracts were developed through the PACE in a Box model which incorporated input from all parties including county staff, lenders, property owners, and contractors.\r\n\r\nThese contracts can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Lender Contract With County</a>\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/t9rfvn9vi0zrbcz/Lender%20Contract%20with%20County.pdf?dl=0\">Owner Contract With County</a>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n	<li><strong>File Assessment Lien</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe end result of a PACE project is a senior lien that will be filed with the local tax assessor/collector.\r\n\r\nThe form for this lien can be found here:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.dropbox.com/s/k5yv0b22m48whn1/Notice%20of%20Assessment%20Lien.pdf?dl=0\">Tax Assessor/Collector Lien</a>', 'Preparing A PACE Project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '160-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:40:11', '2015-04-06 21:40:11', '', '160', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=236', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('237', '2', '2015-04-06 21:42:37', '2015-04-06 21:42:37', '<h1>Who We Are</h1>\r\nThe PACE Financing Authority of Texas was founded as a nonprofit organization in 2015 with the express goal of streamlining the implementation of PACE-funded clean energy projects in Texas. The statute authorizing PACE in Texas (SB 385) was passed by the Texas Legislature in 2013 and is now expanding to counties and municipalities across Texas.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h1>Staff</h1>\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-114\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/charlene-300x278.jpg\" alt=\"Picture of Charlene\" width=\"150\" height=\"139\" />\r\n<h3>Charlene Heydinger\r\nPresident and Chairman of the Board</h3>\r\nCharlene Heydinger serves as the president and board chair of the Texas PACE Authority and as the executive director of Keeping PACE in Texas, a trade association created to promote Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing in Texas. Ms. Heydinger is a public affairs strategist focused on meeting her clients’ legislative and regulatory needs.\r\n\r\nCharlene worked on Capital Hill for over nine years and then as vice president and Washington counsel for ABC, Inc. for nine years. She also served as executive director of the Morton and Angela Topfer Family Foundation. Ms. Heydinger is a member of the Texas, Washington, DC, and Michigan Bar Associations. She is married to Ted Heydinger, is the mother of two young adults and is active in church, school, neighborhood and Scout volunteer activities.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-116\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/jonathan-300x278.jpg\" alt=\"picture of jonathon blackburn\" width=\"150\" height=\"139\" />\r\n<h3>Jonathan Blackburn\r\nChief Executive Officer</h3>\r\n<p class=\"font_7\">Jonathon is the CEO of the Texas PACE Authority and is developing an organization to administer Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) programs in Texas. Prior to moving to Austin, Jonathon lived in the UK and worked for a venture and commercialization firm developing technology startups. He also co-founded a University of Cambridge spin-out that is building a mobile clean energy storage system.  Jonathon started his career as an engineer at the electric utility Southern Company in environmental and energy policy, before moving to its wholesale division developing some of Southern’s first forays into utility-scale renewable energy power plants.</p>\r\n<p class=\"font_7\">Jonathon holds graduate degrees from the University of Cambridge and Duke University. He also has a BS in Chemical Engineering from Mississippi State University.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/joe.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-115\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/joe.jpg\" alt=\"joe\" width=\"150\" height=\"139\" /></a>Joe Edgar\r\nProject Analyst</h3>\r\nJoe is the PACE Project Analyst of the Texas PACE Authority, where he leverages his extensive experience in startup businesses and real estate finance to evaluate PACE project applications.\r\n\r\nPreviously, Joe managed the J4T Venture Fund, a $46.5M fund focused on Texas early-stage companies. He is a member of the U.S. Treasury SSBCI Venture Capital Steering Committee, which aims to share best practices across state lines in regards to venture capital and entrepreneurial ecosystems.\r\n\r\nPrior to managing the J4T Venture Fund Joe was with Texas Governor Perry’s office and managed over $450M in state authority with a focus on early-stage Texas companies. Before joining the governor’s office, he was the Managing Partner of E.I. Investments a $10M fund focused on early-stage investment in Oregon and Texas.', 'About Us', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '113-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-06 21:42:37', '2015-04-06 21:42:37', '', '113', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=237', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('239', '1', '2015-04-07 11:11:18', '2015-04-07 11:11:18', '<a title=\"RSVP Here\" href=\"http://cleantx.org/event/cleantx-forum-keeping-pace-texas/\" target=\"_blank\">cleantx.org/event/cleantx-forum-keeping-pace-texas/</a>\r\n\r\nJoin us on April 28th at 6:00 PM at the Texas Capitol as we team up with Keeping <strong>PACE</strong> in Texas in hosting a forum on Property Assessed Clean Energy (<strong>PACE</strong>).\r\n\r\nOn March 24th, the Commissioners Court of Travis Counted voted to adopt Texas’ first <strong>PACE</strong> program making energy efficiency and renewable energy projects in Travis County eligible to use <strong>PACE</strong> financing.\r\n\r\n<strong>PACE</strong> is an innovative financing program that enables commercial, industrial, multi-family, and agricultural property owners to obtain low-cost, long-term loans for water conservation, energy- efficiency, and renewable energy projects. Participants will then repay those loans through a property assessment.\r\n\r\nJoin us for a celebratory reception and panel discussion of <strong>PACE</strong> and its enabling of affordable clean energy financing. This forum will serve as a kick-off for interested PACE users in Texas, as well as an opportunity to thank the community leaders who made this milestone possible.\r\n\r\nReception: 6:00 pm\r\nPanel: 7:00 pm\r\n\r\n<em>Parking: Public parking garage (E 12th St, Austin, TX 78701) or metered parking (free after 6 pm)</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://cleantx.org/event/cleantx-forum-keeping-pace-texas/\" target=\"_blank\">cleantx.org/event/cleantx-forum-keeping-pace-texas/</a>', 'PACE Forum with CleanTX', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '61-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-07 11:11:18', '2015-04-07 11:11:18', '', '61', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=239', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('240', '1', '2015-04-07 14:23:13', '2015-04-07 14:23:13', '<h3>Welcome to the Texas PACE Authority, Texas’ clean energy marketplace administrator. We\'re facilitating an open-market Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) initiative in Texas to make our buildings more energy and water efficient.</h3>\r\nPACE is an innovative financing program that enables commercial, industrial, multi-family, and agricultural property owners to obtain low-cost, long-term loans for water conservation, energy- efficiency, and renewable energy projects. Participants will then repay those loans through a property assessment.\r\n\r\nPACE has great potential to directly affect the bottom lines of small and medium sized businesses. To be eligible for PACE financing, a project must show that the savings in utility costs will offset the cost of installing the project. In most instances, this will result in an immediate positive cash flow. This mechanism can be used to equip buildings with the latest in efficiency technology, including lighting, HVAC, and water conservation tools. In addition, PACE can be used for renewable energy additions, such as roof-top solar panels.\r\n\r\nThe Texas PACE Authority is a non-profit organization that administers Texas’ new PACE statute by taking a market-based approach to energy finance and economic development. We look forward to working with all parties involved - property owners, contractors, and lenders - in bringing energy and water improvements that are both economically sound and environmentally friendly.', 'Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '4-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-07 14:23:13', '2015-04-07 14:23:13', '', '4', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=240', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('241', '1', '2015-04-08 11:13:17', '2015-04-08 11:13:17', 'The non-profit PACE Financing Authority of Texas is the official administrator of Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs in Texas. PACE is an innovative financing program that enables owners of commercial and industrial properties to obtain low-cost, long-term loans for water conservation, energy-efficiency improvements, and renewable retrofits.\r\n\r\nClick <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3Ota3uvM1E\">here</a> for a short video explaining PACE:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3Ota3uvM1E\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-179 size-medium\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Capture-e1427300183845-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"PACE Infographic\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Property Assessed Clean Energy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '78-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-04-08 11:13:17', '2015-04-08 11:13:17', '', '78', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=241', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_bcyw_posts` VALUES('242', '1', '2015-04-07 19:04:54', '2015-04-07 19:04:54', 'The non-profit PACE Financing Authority of Texas is the official administrator of Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing programs in Texas. PACE is an innovative financing program that enables owners of commercial and industrial properties to obtain low-cost, long-term loans for water conservation, energy-efficiency improvements, and renewable retrofits.\r\n\r\nClick <a href=\"http://https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R3Ota3uvM1E\">here</a> for a short video explaining PACE:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Capture-e1427300183845.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-179\" src=\"http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Capture-e1427300183845-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"PACE Infographic\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Property Assessed Clean Energy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '78-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-07 19:04:54', '2015-04-07 19:04:54', '', '78', 'http://www.texaspaceauthority.org/?p=242', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
